occurrences.line_text: Lightly Cambello leapt downe from his steed,
Cambello it away before had got:
Then first Cambello brought vnto their view
Cambelloes sister was fayre Canacee,
Ne lesse approued was Cambelloes might,
And falling heauie on Cambelloes crest,
Cambelloes armes therefore he on him threw,
Through Cambels shoulder it vnwarely went,
But Cambels fate that fortune did preuent:
And Camber did possesse the Westerne quart,
Cambina with true friendships bond
And wise Cambina taking by her side
And Cambel tooke Cambina to his fere,
But faire Cambina with perswasions myld,
His faire Cambina, couered with a veale;
With Canacee and Cambine linckt in louely bond.
And th'other to the king of Cambria,
Thence doth by Huntingdon and Cambridge flit;
My mother Cambridge, whom as with a Crowne
Cambridge or Oxford, Englands goodly beames.
And that of Cambry king confirmed late,
And by descent from Royall lynage came
Halfe furious vnto his foe he came,
Halfe angry asked him, for what he came.
Came to their wicked maister, and gan tell
When tidings came to me vnhappy maid,
Till weary of their way, they came at last,
He pluckt a bough; out of whose rift there came
And home she came, whereas her mother blynd
Came forth, and finding Kirkrapine there slaine,
Ere long he came, where Vna traueild slow,
And with faire fearefull humblesse towards him shee came.
But that proud Paynim forward came so fierce,
With gaping iawes full greedy at him came,
Soone as the Elfing knight in presence came,
Returne from whence ye came, and rest a while
Came dauncing forth, shaking his deawie haire:
And gorgeous gold arayd I to thee came;
Where when she came, she found the Faery knight
And came to shamefull end. And them beside
By iust occasion to that forrest came,
His louing mother came vpon a day
And now he thither came for like intent;
And soone he came, as he the place had ghest,
With sturdie steps came stalking in his sight,
So willingly she came into his armes,
They sadly traueild thus, vntill they came
In hast came rushing forth from inner bowre,
And after him the proud Duessa came,
Came ramping forth with proud presumpteous gate,
Came hurtling in full fierce, and forst the knight retyre.
Came running fast to greet his victorie,
At last with creeping crooked pace forth came
At last he came vnto an yron doore,
Thither the great Magicien Merlin came,
And gladly did them guide, till to the Hall they came.
O matrone sage (quoth she) I hither came,
Loe two most goodly virgins came in place,
And labours long, through which ye hither came,
And came to Coelia to declare her smart,
And lodging, vnto all that came, and went:
So came to Vna, who him ioyd to see,
Forth came that auncient Lord and aged Queene,
Vnto that doughtie Conquerour they came,
The comely virgins came, with girlands dight,
Vntill they came, where that faire virgin stood;
With chearefull vew; who when to her they came,
But when they came, where that dead Dragon lay,
So fairely dight, when she in presence came,
Came running in, much like a man dismaid,
When with king Oberon he came to Faerie land.
Through woods & mountaines, till they came at last
By this his aged guide in presence came;
Lucina came: a manchild forth I brought:
Till that at last they to a Castle came,
Newes hereof to her other sisters came,
But still when Guyon came to part their fight,
Came with them eke, all were they wondrous loth,
To tell from whence he came through ieopardie,
Sith earst into this forrest wild I came.
One day vnto me came in friendly mood,
Eftsoones he came vnto th'appointed place,
When he in presence came, to Guyon first
Came to a riuer, by whose vtmost brim
The varlet saw, when to the flood he came,
By fortune came, led with the troublous sowne:
At last he came vnto a gloomy glade,
At length they came into a larger space,
Till that they came vnto an yron dore,
Some scumd the drosse, that from the metall came;
They neuer creature saw, that came that way.
By this that straunger knight in presence came,
They thither marcht: but when they came in sight,
Came to the Ladies eare, which there did dwell,
Both guestes and meate, when euer in they came,
Soone as the gracious Alma came in place,
(O hideous hunger of dominion) hither came.
Hither came Ioseph of Arimathy,
And of those forreiners, which came from farre,
Vntill he came vnto a standing lake;
Came rushing in the fomy waues enrold,
Vntill they came in vew of those wild beasts:
Which thither came: but in the Porch there sate
Till that he came vnto another gate,
The way they came, the same retourn'd they right,
But fiercely forward came withouten dread,
With her on foot, and stoutly forward came;
At length they came into a forrest wyde,
At last as nigh out of the wood she came,
As did this knight, before ye hither came.
Where when confusedly they came, they fownd
For such intent into these parts I came,
From whence to none inferiour ye came,
They came, as Merlin them directed late:
Tydings hereof came to his mothers eare;
At last they came vnto a double way,
Chase her away, from whence she came, to hell.
Of whom he asked, whence he lately came,
Tho to his brethren came: for they were three
The gentle Squire came ryding that same way,
Shortly she came, whereas that woefull Squire
Shortly vnto the wastefull woods she came,
To Faery court she came, where many one
So long she trauelled, till at length she came
And came at last in weary wretched plight
And slew him cruelly, ere any reskew came.
As seeming sory, that she euer came
Fiercely that stranger forward came, and nigh
Tho rudely askt her, how she thither came.
Came to that Castle, and with earnest mone,
He came, which full of guests he found whyleare,
Ne would they eate, till she in presence came.
She came in presence with right comely grace,
And with them sayling thence, to th'Isle of Paros came.
Gaue them safe conduct, till to end they came:
They spide, where Paridell came pricking fast
But let him passe as lightly, as he came:
Came dauncing forth, and with them nimbly led
Ne stayd he, till he came vnto the place,
Till that he came vnto a rockie hill,
That she at last came to a fountaine sheare,
And stoutly came vnto the Castle gate;
Came riding on a Lion rauenous,
And passage bard to all, that thither came,
At last she came vnto the place, where late
It so befell one euening, that they came
And eke so short, that seemd their ends out shortly came.
Which doen the doughty chalenger came forth,
Now stood, came forth in hast to take his part,
To Ladies loue, where so he came in place,
And all that while, where so they rode or came,
Vnto the place of turneyment they came;
Then first of all forth came Sir Satyrane,
Till that he came, where he had Cambell seene,
The last day came, when all those knightes againe
Seuen Knights one after other as they came:
And beating downe, what euer nigh him came,
Much wondred all men, what, or whence he came,
And ouerthrew, what euer came her neare,
And each one thought, as to their fancies came.
Then looke to whom she voluntarie came,
She came of her accord, in spight of all his fone.
And vnto her his congee came to take.
Ran, till he came to th'end of all his way,
To which I boldly came vpon my feeble feete.
Came to the caue, and rolling thence the stone,
Might issue forth, came rudely rushing in,
And follow'd fast: but when he came in sight,
His owne deare Lord Prince Arthure came that way,
Vntill she came where wonned his Belphebe faire.
A Squire came gallopping, as he would flie;
Him ouertooke, before he came in vew.
Came to that Squire, yet trembling euery vaine:
Ouer his head, before the harme came neare.
With which he killed all, that came within his might.
This Gyants daughter came vpon a day
Whereof when tydings came vnto mine eare,
In steed of whom forth came I Placidas,
The Tyrant selfe came forth with yelling bray,
In presence came, desirous t'vnderstand
Came forth full weake and wan, not like him selfe to bee.
At length they came, whereas a troupe of Knights
And to the place of perill shortly came.
Till to the Bridges vtter gate I came:
Into the inmost Temple thus I came,
In order as they came, could I recount them well.
First came great Neptune with his threeforkt mace,
And after them the royall issue came,
Next came the aged Ocean, and his Dame,
For all the rest of those two parents came,
And after him the famous riuers came,
Soone after whom the louely Bridegroome came,
Then came his neighbour flouds, which nigh him dwell,
And there came Stoure with terrible aspect,
Then came the Rother, decked all with woods
Next these the plenteous Ouse came far from land,
Next these came Tyne, along whose stony bancke
Then came those sixe sad brethren, like forlorne,
These after, came the stony shallow Lone,
Then came the Bride, the louely Medua came,
Then came the Bride, the louely Medua came,
Who thither with her came, to learne and see
So backe he came vnto her patient;
Vnto himselfe she came, and him besought,
Apollo came; who soone as he had sought
For that a waift, the which by fortune came
But it would pierce or cleaue, where so it came;
There came this knight, hauing in companie
When to the place they came, where Artegall
Vnto the place he came within a while,
A villaine to them came with scull all raw,
And them against came all that list to giust,
Appear'd in heauen, into the field they came,
The third day came, that should due tryall lend
Sir Artegall into the Tilt-yard came,
Came to the open hall, to listen whose
And thether also came in open sight
Who came not forth, but for Sir Artegall
Came Braggadochio, and did shew his shield,
And then to him came fayrest Florimell,
Forth from the thickest preasse of people came,
Came forth into the rout, and them t'array began.
So forth she came out of the citty gate,
Then forth came Artegall out of his tent,
Soone after eke came she, with fell intent,
She to a window came, that opened West,
With that there came vnto her chamber dore
Till to the perillous Bridge she came, and there
Stayd not, till she came to her selfe againe,
For all that euer came within his reach,
Her selfe came in, her glory to partake;
At last when as to her owne Loue she came,
So forth he came all in a cote of plate,
He came vnto his caue, and there did vew
But not for those she now in question came,
And with him to make part against her, came
First there came Pittie, with full tender hart,
And then came Daunger threatning hidden dread,
Then came Nobilitie of birth, that bread
There came two Springals of full tender yeares,
And came to this, where Belge then did dwell,
For well she wist this knight came, succour to supply.
They came vnto a Citie farre vp land,
To whom when tydings thereof came, he streight
Ne stayed step, till that he came at last
But opening streight the Sparre, forth to him came,
So to the Church he came, where it was told,
To many a one, which came vnto her schoole,
Came dauncing forth, and ioyous carrols song:
And deeme it doen of will, that through inforcement came.
At last they came whereas that Ladie bode,
Tho when they came to the sea coast, they found
By this came tydings to the Tyrants eare,
He thether came, but for to trie the right
Who came at length, with proud presumpteous gate,
Thence passing forth, into the hall he came,
But ere he came in place, that youth had kild
Came to the place, whereas ye heard afore
Till to that Ladies fathers house he came;
Came to the place, where he his Lady found
But when as Calepine came to the brim,
By this the other came in place likewise,
Came to her creeping like a fawning hound,
How euer by hard hap he hether came;
All arm'd to point came ryding thetherward,
He came, whose couert stopt his further sight,
Till towards night they came vnto a plaine,
In piteous languor, since ye hither came,
Ne stayd, till that he came into the hall:
Ere long to him a homely groome there came,
Came forth in hast: where when as with the dead
So did his forty yeomen, which there with him came.
At last he vp into the chamber came,
Ere long they came, whereas in euill tyde
Came running in, and whilest on ground he lay,
To seeke for booty, came by fortune blynde,
Then came to them a good old aged syre,
By which home came the fayrest Pastorell,
And euer when him came in companie,
When to the Caue they came, they found it fast:
Still slew the formost, that came first to hand,
And all that nere him came, did hew and slay,
That to his loue sometimes he came in place,
Came to the place, where when he wrapped found
At all, that came within his rauenings,
As euer could Cameleon colours new;
Vpon a Camell loaden all with gold;
Proud Sisera, and how Camill' hath slaine
All in a Camis light of purple silke
Of Camphara, and Calamint, and Dill,
To Faery court thou cam'st to seeke for fame,
Till thou cam'st hither to augment our mone,
All in a silken Camus lylly whight,
Much can they prayse the trees so straight and hy,
His forces faile, ne can no longer fight.
That from their noyance he no where can rest,
Of a straunge man I can you tidings tell,
He that the stubborne Sprites can wisely tame,
A fit false dreame, that can delude the sleepers sent.
Tho can she weepe, to stirre vp gentle ruth,
And oft would flie away. O who can tell
But this good knight soone as he them can spie,
O how can beautie maister the most strong,
For many yeares of sorrow can dispence:
With blustring breath of heauen, that none can bide,
And in his hand did beare a bouzing can,
His dronken corse he scarse vpholden can,
Euen stout Sans foy (O who can then refrayn?)
With gentle wordes he can her fairely greet,
Why dame (quoth he) what oddes can euer bee,
And eke enchaunted armes, that none can perce,
Ne none can wound the man, that does them wield.
Can neuer rest, vntill it forth haue brought
Can tune their timely voyces cunningly,
And many Chroniclers, that can record
And softly can embalme on euery side.
And can the children of faire light deface.
But who can turne the streame of destinee,
And handle softly, till they can be healed:
Thou biddest me to eeke? Can Night defray
How can ye vengeance iust so long withhold,
Can now deuise to quit a thrall from such a plight?
Where none appeares can make her selfe a way:
The lesser pangs can beare, who hath endur'd the chiefe.
To seeme like Truth, whose shape she well can faine,
That none can breath, nor see, nor heare at will,
For earthly sight can nought but sorow breed,
Who hath endur'd the whole, can beare each part.
Can heart, so plung'd in sea of sorrowes deepe,
And can more easily be thought, then said.
Flesh may empaire (quoth he) but reason can repaire.
Or that your prowesse can me yield reliefe:
Can speake his prowesse, that did earst you beare,
But all in vaine: no fort can be so strong,
Ne fleshly brest can armed be so sound,
What iustice can but iudge against thee right,
Who then can striue with strong necessitie,
As Eagles eye, that can behold the Sunne:
Who better can the way to heauen aread,
Cannot describe, nor wit of man can tell;
The fairest peece, that eye beholden can:
For bloud can nought but sin, & wars but sorrowes yield.
To throw his rider: who can quickly ryse
Ne can Cephise, nor Hebrus match this well:
Can high aduance his broad discoloured brest,
From loathed soile he can him lightly reare,
How can I tell, but that his talants may
As that your daughter can ye well aduize,
Ne I against the same can iustly preace:
That none but death for euer can deuide;
But vouch antiquities, which no body can know.
What comfort can I wofull wretch conceaue,
I present was, and can it witnesse well,
So can he turne his earnest vnto game,
Well mote yee thee, as well can wish your thought,
Yet can they not warne death from wretched wight.
My tongue can tell, so farre all sense they pas:
Betwixt them both can measure out a meane,
With goodly meanes to pacifie, well as he can.
Thou little wotest, what this right hand can:
Ne can the man, that moulds in idle cell,
For who can tell (and sure I feare it ill)
That Monster can be maistred or destroyd:
As steele can wound, or strength can ouerthroe.
As steele can wound, or strength can ouerthroe.
Faire Sir (quoth he) what man can shun the hap,
Happy, who can abstaine, when Rancour rife
Strikes in the stocke, ne thence can be rel[e]ast,
Can call out of the bodies of fraile wightes:
So strongly, that vneathes it can refraine
And foes of life, she better can restraine;
Can chaunge my cheare, or make me euer mourne;
My litle boat can safely passe this perilous bourne.
Yet no man to them can his carefull paines compare.
Ah well away, most noble Lords, how can
And soyld with durtie gore, that no man can
Yet nought can quench mine inly flaming syde,
Nothing but death can doe me to respire.
Burning in flames, yet no flames can I see,
Ne can be quencht, within my secret bowels bee.
That money can thy wantes at will supply?
It can puruay in twinckling of an eye;
What secret place (quoth he) can safely hold
That none without the same enduren can.
That I can carue with this inchaunted brond
But him henceforth the same can saue no more;
Yet no where can her find: such happinesse
That haue twelue moneths sought one, yet no where can her find.
O who can tell the prayses of that makers might!
Ne can I tell, ne can I stay to tell
Ne can I tell, ne can I stay to tell
Ne can deuized be of mortall wit;
That well can witnesse yet vnto this day
For neither can he fly, nor other harme,
All passengers, that none from it can shift:
She them espying, loud to them can call,
Th'infernall feends with it he can asswage,
And Orcus tame, whom nothing can perswade,
That natures worke by art can imitate:
More subtile web Arachne can not spin,
Nor life-resembling pencill it can paint,
Who can it doe more liuely, or more trew,
For who can shun the chaunce, that dest'ny doth ordaine?
In shame of knighthood, as I largely can report.
For which no reason can find remedy.
Salue to your sore, yet loue can higher stye,
Can doe (said she) that, which cannot be donne.
Ne can my running sore find remedie,
For who with reason can you aye reproue,
Can haue no end, nor hope of my desire,
That well can witnesse, who by triall it does proue.
Or what needs her to toyle, sith fates can make
And if he then with victorie can lin,
How can they other do, sith both are bold and blind?
But ah, who can deceiue his destiny,
Ne can thy irreuocable destiny be weft?
And yeeld her roome to day, that can it gouerne well.
But can ye read Sir, how I may her find, or where.
What can I lesse do, then her loue therefore,
But that sweet Cordiall, which can restore
Ne poysnous Enuy iustly can empaire
So faire a place, as Nature can deuize:
But nought that wanteth rest, can long aby.
That now no more we can the maine-land see,
But yet what so my feeble Muse can frame,
Can guilen Argus, when she list misdonne?
That can withhold her wilfull wandring feet;
And you most noble Lord, that can and dare
Yet can he neuer dye, but dying liues,
Ne none can suffer to approchen neare:
In wauering wemens wit, that none can tell,
Ah who can loue the worker of her smart?
Can wretched Lady, quit from wofull state,
Both foolish knights, I can but laugh at both,
What vengeance due can equall thy desart,
None but a God or godlike man can slake;
And she so farre astray, as none can tell.
Ne certes can that friendship long endure,
Not all the gods can chaunge, nor Ioue him self can free.
Not all the gods can chaunge, nor Ioue him self can free.
He can let driue at him with all his power,
With all the strength and stifnesse that he can.
They vp againe them selues can lightly reare,
That can her best defend from villenie;
As like can not be seene from East to West,
What medicine can any Leaches art
He wondred much. But th'other thus can say;
To dight, to welcome him, well as she can:
That her enhaunced hand she downe can soft withdraw.
I can not vnto you aread a right.
With sufferaunce soft, which rigour can abate,
Striuing to comfort him all that they can,
I neither can my loue, ne yet my life forgo.
Blessed the man that well can vse his blis:
Ne can be cured of that cruell stroke
How can they all in this so narrow verse
Can from all men so rich a kingdome hold;
With many more, whose names no tongue can tell.
And she, that with her least word can asswage
Can hardly but by Sacrament be tride,
And they with aire, that not a drop can slide:
Ill can he rule the great, that cannot reach the small.
But what on earth can alwayes happie stand?
As by no meanes he can himselfe outwind.
All suddenly, ere one can looke aside,
Ladies can laugh at Ladies, Knights at Knights,
What better dowre can to a dame be hight?
But whether it be so or no, I can not say.
But who can scape, what his owne fate hath wrought?
Can dread of ought your dreadlesse hart withhold,
For such your kind regard, I can but rest your detter.
And try if thou by faire entreatie, can
The art of mightie words, that men can charme;
Can yeeld great thankes for such her curtesie,
The rest my selfe too readily can spell.
Ne can be stild for all his nurses might,
But his owne doome, that none can now vndoo.
Can from th'immortall Gods ought hidden bee?
That can with melting pleasaunce mollifye
So can they both them selues full eath perswade
Can not come neare him in the couert wood,
A dreadfull depth, how deepe no man can tell;
Can follow out those false footsteps of his,
Ne none can backe returne, that once are gone amis.
Who then can thee, Mercilla, throughly prayse,
Who then can thinke their hedlong ruine to recure.
And can let driue at him so dreadfullie,
What guerdon can I giue thee for thy paine,
To rend and teare, what so she can oppresse;
None can haue tidings to assist her side.
That none can there arriue without an hoste:
Yet can I not my loue haue nathemore;
Can keepe from outrage, and from doing wrong,
No faith so firme, no trust can be so strong,
Ne none can find, but who was taught them by the Muse.
Yet is that glasse so gay, that it can blynd
Which haue so goodly, as ye can deuize,
And spoile my selfe, that can not thee withstand?
How can he mercy euer hope to haue?
His mightie hart their mournefull case can rew,
